choices.text:
trying to have read more than my age group. I like to have read more so I could contribute to conversations and openly discuss the content of the story or an article or a poem. The smallest age-group I target is eighteen, to be able to have something to discuss with my readers who are the same age.

I also read many books and articles unrelated to religion and spirituality. It is quite enjoyable to have a book on highly regarded math methods and books on spirituality from the different faiths. Reading suits my needs for certain amount of entertainment, to be in touch with my emotions and to analyze, synthesize, and evaluate information and theories. Indeed, I don’t think of reading as entertainment, but as a needed alternative to other wasteful endeavors. Always at the back of my mind, is a chapter on ‘information management.’ It’s why to love the library.

The largest walk or simply just vision and feel of a story that ran across my mind. A large chunk is easily cut back to a more concise piece. The only freedom I grant myself is when an image comes to mind, poor as it seems with no solid grounding and maybe with weak structure. All I allow myself is to let it come to life, to be rewritten, or to be modified and changed before I stop. With themes, I try to resume them through a few exercises that complement and build off one another; otherwise it can be repetitive and tedious.

Always to go back to what prompted the creation of the note
